    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">- 40 NESDC staff trained in Foresight and Horizon Scanning.
- A road map developed for a tourism led development within Andaman sub region - (Phuket, Krabi, Phang-nga), including vision (position of this area) and potential flagship projects and supporting strategy.
- A quantitative survey and social listening report that identifies policy issue with further insights.
- An initial research conducted on two selected policy issues: social protection and innovation.
- A virtual training event conducted to enhance the capacity of policy makers and educators at the national and sub-national - A Desk review conducted on existing virtual platforms for policy innovation.
- One online event organized to facilitate a cross-border exchange on innovative tools and processes.
- Five policy talks organized to bring together experts to share their knowledge and experience with a community of public innovators and the public in Thailand to raise awareness of the importance of policy innovation in crisis management.
- One seminar organized to raise awareness and mobilize stakeholders to take collective responsibility to fight against sexual and gender-based violence, applying the Casual Layer Analysis tool.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">- 40 NESDC staff trained in Foresight and Horizon Scanning. The training also led to an open dialogue on the challenges of tourism in Thailand in post-COVID and how-to response in terms of policy formulation and innovation and a creation of a list of the development effects and the trends in the re-imagining and re-development of the tourism sector. 
- An introductory knowledge sharing session on the Portfolio Approach conducted for the NESDC. In addition, the Thailand Policy Lab conducted in-depth exploration and experimentation with the systems design and portfolio approach using tourism as the topic for experimentation, which produced a draft of Policy Options for Sustainable Tourism in Thailand for Phuket and Bangkok.
- Quantitative research conducted on youth with sample size of approximately 1,000. Report from the survey showed the trend of emerging issues of Thai youth. The topics investigated included: sexual reproductive health/teenage pregnancy, mental health and wellbeing, substances and alcohol abuse, prevalence of road accidents, accessibility, equality and quality education, healthcare provision and accessibility for youth, air pollution and effects on climate change, youth gender equality and diversity, youth poverty &amp; employment.
- Research conducted on two selected policy issues: social protection and innovation as a basis for creating a journey of policy ideas and the embedded mindset and principles of these two issues. In addition, a roundtable discussion was conducted to introduce tools and for policymakers to reflect on the current policymaking.
- 50 lecturers from 15 universities across different regions in Thailand participated in the online training event on policy innovation tools. The training led to the incorporation of innovative tools in the curriculum in three universities: (1) Hopes and Fears, Signals and Drivers, Scenario Matrix being implemented at King Mongkuts Institute of Technology Ladkrabang; (2) Futures Wheel, Winners and Losers being implemented at Thammasat University; and (3) Community Engagement Prep Canvas being implemented at Chulalongkorn University.
- 776 participants (including representatives from government, academic, private sectors as well as non-governmental organizations) participated in the Policy Innovation Exchange forum from 28 countries. The event achieved a 33% increase in recognition of the importance of innovation in policymaking, while maintaining an average satisfaction level of speakers and content digestibility of 92% (post-event survey).
- A proposed concept developed for the virtual innovation platform and proposed design models for the platform, including key features, technical architecture.
- Five policy talks conducted on the following themes: tourism, local economy, upskilling/reskilling, crisis management and migrant labour. This platform shared knowledge and cultivate good practices on innovation while exploring the opportunity for innovative policy making processes in addressing contemporary issues and challenges.
- 39 participants from academia and local government attended the Women in Policy Making and Gender Equality in Public Policy/Public Service Delivery seminar. With the use of a Casual Layer Analysis tool, the seminar inspired new thinking and innovation in gender and gender-based violence related policies and increased awareness at all levels of government on the importance of gender as a way of conceptualizing information</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
